==Spanish==
===Etymology===
Latin ''[[gustare]]''

===Verb===
'''gustar'''
# To be pleasing.
# To [[taste]].

===Usage notes===

''Gustarle'' (to be pleasing to) is usually translated to English with the verb to [[like]].  This causes confusion for some English speakers studying Spanish, because the object of ''gustarle'' is the person to whom it is pleasing, rather than in English where that person is the subject.

In such a sentence with ''gustar'' in Spanish, the verb agrees with ''what is liked'', and the indirect object pronoun (me, te, le, les, os, nos) agrees with ''the person that is doing the liking''.

===Conjugations===

*Me gusta - I like (lit. It is pleasing to me.)
*Te gusta - You (sing.) like (lit. It is pleasing to you.)
*Le gusta - He/She/It likes (lit. It is pleasing to him.)
<p>
*No me gusta - (negetive)I don't like
*No me gusta nada - (negetive)I don't like at all
<p>
*Me gusta mucho - I like a lot
<p>
*Me gustan las [[matemáticas]] - I like maths a lot

